The crash is caused by a double free of `b->name`.

At the point of the crash:

```c
static void destroy_blob(blob_t *b) {
    if (!b) return;
    free(b->name);          /* crash: b->name was already freed */
    free(b);
}
```

`b` itself is still a valid allocated `blob_t`, but its `name` field points to memory that was already freed earlier in `load_blob()`.

Walkthrough:

```c
int main(void) {
    blob_t *b = load_blob("abcdef");
```

`main()` calls:

```c
load_blob("abcdef")
```

Inside `load_blob()`:

```c
blob_t *b = (blob_t *)malloc(sizeof(*b));
```

A `blob_t` is allocated. So now:

```c
b != NULL
```

Then:

```c
b->name = strdup(name);
b->size = 0;
```

Because `name` is `"abcdef"`, `strdup()` allocates a new heap buffer containing `"abcdef"` and stores its address in `b->name`.

So the state is approximately:

```c
b = 0x6020000000d0
b->name = <heap pointer to "abcdef">
b->size = 0
```

Then this branch is taken:

```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    free(b->name);      /* release the name on the recoverable error path */
    b->size = 0;
    return b;           /* hand the partially-initialised blob back */
}
```

Because:

```c
strlen("abcdef") == 6
```

and `6 > 4`, the recoverable error path runs.

The important defect is here:

```c
free(b->name);
```

After this call, the heap allocation owned by `b->name` is released. However, `b->name` is not changed. It still contains the old pointer value, but that pointer is now dangling.

So after `load_blob()` returns, the state is:

```c
b != NULL
b->size == 0
b->name == <dangling pointer to already-freed memory>
```

Then `main()` does:

```c
if (b && b->size == 0) {
    fprintf(stderr, "load_blob: empty blob, cleaning up\n");
}
```

This condition is true because `b` is non-null and `b->size` is `0`. But this block only prints a message; it does not repair or clear `b->name`.

Then:

```c
destroy_blob(b);
```

Inside `destroy_blob()`:

```c
free(b->name);
```

This attempts to free the same allocation that was already freed in `load_blob()`.

That is why AddressSanitizer reports:

```text
Deallocation of freed memory
```

The root cause is that `load_blob()` returns a `blob_t` whose destructor is expected to own and free `b->name`, but `load_blob()` has already freed `b->name` and left the pointer dangling.

There is an ownership invariant violation:

```c
destroy_blob()` assumes:
    if b->name is non-NULL, it points to live heap memory owned by b.

load_blob()` violates that by returning:
    b->name points to already-freed heap memory.
```

A freed pointer must not remain in an object that will later be passed to a destructor that frees that field.

##### Recommendation

Minimal local fix: after freeing `b->name` in the recoverable error path, set it to `NULL`.

```c
static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {
    blob_t *b = malloc(sizeof(*b));
    if (!b) return NULL;

    b->name = strdup(name);
    b->size = 0;

    if (!b->name) {
        free(b);
        return NULL;
    }

    /* Simulated recoverable parse error. */
    if (strlen(name) > 4) {
        free(b->name);
        b->name = NULL;      /* important: prevent later double free */
        b->size = 0;
        return b;
    }

    b->size = strlen(b->name);
    return b;
}
```

With this fix, `destroy_blob()` remains safe because:

```c
free(NULL);
```

is a no-op in C.

A more thorough root-cause fix is to make the ownership contract consistent. Either return a fully valid object whose destructor owns all fields, or return `NULL`/an error on failure.

For example, if the caller should receive an “empty blob”, then return a valid empty blob with no owned name:

```c
static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {
    blob_t *b = malloc(sizeof(*b));
    if (!b) return NULL;

    b->name = strdup(name);
    b->size = 0;

    if (!b->name) {
        free(b);
        return NULL;
    }

    if (strlen(name) > 4) {
        free(b->name);
        b->name = NULL;
        b->size = 0;
        return b;
    }

    b->size = strlen(b->name);
    return b;
}
```

Alternatively, if a parse error means the blob should not be returned at all, clean up completely and return `NULL`:

```c
static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {
    blob_t *b = malloc(sizeof(*b));
    if (!b) return NULL;

    b->name = strdup(name);
    b->size = 0;

    if (!b->name) {
        free(b);
        return NULL;
    }

    if (strlen(name) > 4) {
        free(b->name);
        free(b);
        return NULL;
    }

    b->size = strlen(b->name);
    return b;
}
```

Then `main()` can handle that cleanly:

```c
int main(void) {
    blob_t *b = load_blob("abcdef");

    if (!b) {
        fprintf(stderr, "load_blob failed\n");
        return 1;
    }

    if (b->size == 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "load_blob: empty blob, cleaning up\n");
    }

    destroy_blob(b);
    printf("done\n");
    return 0;
}
```

The key rule is: if `destroy_blob()` is responsible for freeing `b->name`, then `load_blob()` must not return a `blob_t` containing a dangling `name` pointer. Either leave ownership to the destructor, or clear the pointer after freeing it.

